https://t.co/CeMQVqb5Jn

so i pondered what video of them would show their love for each other, definitively, no questions remaining, to a person who doesn’t know who they are at all. and you gotta think about what it was like the first time you watched a video of theirs. it’s confusing. they move and +

but what I had to think about was how to prove this to someone who doesn’t know them? we know about their love from watching their content, but you can’t show 20 videos to someone who doesn’t care about them, and if you only show 1 video it could be said that it’s just for show.

but his explanation had me stumped for a minute. of course I knew the answer was OBVIOUSLY: no that wouldn’t work. their love makes them special and can’t be replicated. i even said “i don’t think they’d be able to go on without 1 member.”

but he elaborated: “but if 1 member left the fans would still love the other 6. they would stay for the 6 even if a new person joined. after a while they would grow to love the new person.” and it’s pretty fucking smart and it might work?? for a group that’s not bangtan.

Inspired by my teen brother who was trying to be an asshole but was also being clever when he asked: “Could BTS exist forever if they kept adding new members everytime an old member left?” My first reaction was “well I think their fans would notice if a member got replaced…”

if anyone ever genuinely asks what is special about bts, what ACTUALLY makes them different, well, I think we all know the answer is love. But how do you explain that to a non-fan? Easy: Teach them about pyschological mirroring. Then show a video of bts doing it.

i had no idea how harmful the anti-diet/anti-vegan stuff was until I was diagnosed with my first autoimmune disease. I’d been a server for years and no one at any of the places i worked had ever taken gluten free seriously. we were all so uneducated.

don’t be mad at people with diet restrictions. instead, examine the system that causes people to take this route. 

I know the anti-diet stuff is fueled by the body positivity movement. but we need to understand that people with dietary restrictions ≠ people who are fatphobic.
